\begin_layout Standard
As affine transformations, the mappings are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{gathered}\mathbf{x}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x};\qquad\mathbf{x}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0
\end{array}\right];\\
\mathbf{x}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right];\qquad\mathbf{x}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & -\frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{1}{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right].
\end{gathered}
\]

\end_inset

For the second dissection, remember all the triangles are similar, so correspond
ing parts are in proportion.
 In particular, the smallest triangle is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

 scaled version of the whole and the remaining part is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

 scaled version.
 Getting a little ahead of ourselves, transformations mapping the whole
 triangle to the two parts are, in words,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
scale by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

, reflect about the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-axis, rotate by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 (counterclockwise about the origin), then translate along line segment
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

; and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
scale by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

, reflect about the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis, rotate by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $-\theta$
\end_inset

 (clockwise about the origin), then translate along line segment 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To quantify the rotations and translations, we need to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and the sines and cosines of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Using the Pythagorean theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{2}=x^{2}+\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

, and the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x\cos\beta,x\sin\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\beta=\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\beta=\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta=\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}$
\end_inset

, so the mappings are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}\mapsto\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\beta & -\sin\beta\\
\sin\beta & \cos\beta
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{4}{5}
\end{array}\right];\ \mathbf{x}\mapsto\frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\theta & \sin\theta\\
-\sin\theta & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{4}{5}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

which simplify as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{x}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{1}{5} & -\frac{2}{5}\\
-\frac{2}{5} & \frac{1}{5}
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{4}{5}
\end{array}\right];\qquad\mathbf{x}\mapsto\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{4}{5} & -\frac{2}{5}\\
-\frac{2}{5} & -\frac{4}{5}
\end{array}\right]\mathbf{x}+\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{2}{5}\\
\frac{4}{5}
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset


